  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: Five Minutes a Week, Honestly" imageAlt="Jack Russell Terrier puppy being brushed after a walk" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Grooming is where the Jack Russell hands you back all the time the exercise takes. The smooth coat needs a weekly once-over with a brush; broken and rough coats add an occasional tidy-up. No salon schedule, no mats, no topknots, and baths only when the adventures demand it.</p>
      <p>Two honest notes: the white coat sheds more visibly than people expect, especially smooth coats, so the brush is really shed-control; and this breed's grooming budget goes to nail trims instead, because all that running needs well-kept feet. Both tools are in your starter kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Jack Russell Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Jack Russell Terrier puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Jack Russell goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. Health is the breed's proudest statistic: bred for function rather than looks, the Jack Russell is one of the soundest dogs in existence, which is how it earns that 13-to-16-year lifespan. The short list worth knowing: patellar luxation, the small-dog kneecap issue; lens luxation, an inherited eye condition in some lines, worth asking about; and Legg-Calvé-Perthes, a hip condition occasionally seen in small terriers.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. Portion to the actual exercise done; see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="The Fine Print on Singapore's Cutest Working Dog" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>Jack Russells star in enough films and ads that the face arrives pre-sold, so here is the fine print, from people who match dogs to homes for a living. This breed can jump five times its height, dig with professional intent, learn to open latches by watching you, and hold a grudge against a squirrel for years. None of that is a defect; it's the job description it was bred for.</p>
      <p>Channelled into exercise, games and training, those traits make the best small dog many owners will ever have. Left to idle in a quiet flat, they make viral videos of destroyed sofas. The variable isn't the dog; it's the routine you bring. That's the whole truth, and it's why we interview Jack Russell buyers as much as they interview us.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">Built into the breed</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'Jumps and climbs; secure the balcony',
            'Digs and chews when under-exercised',
            'Real prey drive around small animals',
          ].map((fact) => (
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-cream-700)]">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" class="mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-[var(--color-coral-500)]" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M18 6 6 18M6 6l12 12" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" />
              </svg>
              {fact}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CaptionedBlock>

    <PawTrail bg="bg-[var(--color-surface)]" colorClass="text-[var(--color-coral-300)]" />
  </div>

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Jack Russell's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Jack Russell puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Jack Russell explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and predictable, which for this breed means structured play in short bursts, a fixed feeding routine, and the toilet pads where we placed them. Don't let the puppy leap off furniture while joints are growing, and yes, it will try.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks and the engine warms up. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week without fail; for this breed early training is the difference between a partner and a project. See <a href="/free-training/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

